# Deploy to: /etc/default/cpufrequtils on Pi
#
# Prerequisites:
#   sudo apt install cpufrequtils
#
# The cpufrequtils service reads this file at boot and sets the CPU governor.
#
# Governor choices:
#   conservative  - Scales CPU frequency up gradually when load increases,
#                   scales back down when idle. Best for battery life on
#                   interactive workloads. Does NOT starve keyboard/input.
#   powersave     - Locks CPU at minimum frequency. Can cause input latency
#                   on compact keyboards. Avoid on this build.
#   performance   - Locks CPU at maximum frequency. Burns battery fast.
#                   1200mAh LiPo will not last. Avoid on this build.
#
# On Bookworm, raspberrypi-sys-mods may also set the governor via udev rules.
# cpufrequtils takes precedence after its service starts at boot.
# If governor reverts to ondemand/schedutil, check:
#   systemctl status cpufrequtils
#
# Verification (after reboot):
#   cat /sys/devices/system/cpu/cpu0/cpufreq/scaling_governor
#   -> should output: conservative
#
#   cpufreq-info
#   -> shows current governor, available frequencies, and per-core status

GOVERNOR="conservative"
